<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="355" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="355">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="355">
Unmodified antennae, hindwings lacking patches of scales, as in 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. rara" pageId="0" pageNumber="355" rank="species" species="rara">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="355">M. rara</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with a body length of 2 mm. Abdominal segment VI without sternite process.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="355" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="355">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="355">
Dark brown coloration (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Female specimen of Mejicanotrichia harrisi Bueno-Soria &amp; Barba-Alvarez, 1999 A habitus, dorsal B head, dorsal C segments VI-X of abdomen, ventral D bursa copulatrix ventral. Scale bars: 1 mm (A); 800 µm (B); 200 µm (C); 30 µm (D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1111.77413.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/712649" pageId="0" pageNumber="355">3A</figureCitation>
). Body. Range length: 2.3-2.5 mm.
</paragraph>
<caption doi="10.3897/zookeys.1111.77413.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/712649" pageId="0" pageNumber="355" start="Figure 3" startId="F3">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="355">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="355">Figure 3.</emphasis>
Female specimen of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bueno-Soria &amp; Barba-Alvarez" authorityYear="1999" class="Insecta" family="Hydroptilidae" genus="Mejicanotrichia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mejicanotrichia harrisi" order="Trichoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="355" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="harrisi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="355">Mejicanotrichia harrisi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Bueno-Soria &amp; 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Barba-Álvarez">Barba-Alvarez</normalizedToken>
, 1999 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="355">A</emphasis>
habitus, dorsal 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="355">B</emphasis>
head, dorsal 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="355">C</emphasis>
segments VI-X of abdomen, ventral 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="355">D</emphasis>
bursa copulatrix ventral. Scale bars: 1 mm (
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="355">A</emphasis>
); 800 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
(
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="355">B</emphasis>
); 200 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
(
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="355">C</emphasis>
); 30 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
(
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="355">D</emphasis>
).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="355">
<emphasis bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="355">Head.</emphasis>
Antennae simple, 17-segmented, scape slightly longer than flagellum; three ocelli present (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Female specimen of Mejicanotrichia harrisi Bueno-Soria &amp; Barba-Alvarez, 1999 A habitus, dorsal B head, dorsal C segments VI-X of abdomen, ventral D bursa copulatrix ventral. Scale bars: 1 mm (A); 800 µm (B); 200 µm (C); 30 µm (D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1111.77413.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/712649" pageId="0" pageNumber="355">3B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="355">
<emphasis bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="355">Thorax.</emphasis>
Wings with reduced venation, mesoscutellum with a transverse line and subrectangular metascutellum. Tibial formula (0, 2, 4). Legs unmodified.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="355">
<emphasis bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="355">Abdomen.</emphasis>
Segment VII elongated, without processes on sternite. Segment VIII short and ring-shaped, with a fringe of setae on posterior margin and a pair of apodemes extending anteriorly. Segment IX short, with pair of apodemes originating on posterolateral margin and extending anteriorly just before anterior margin of segment VII. Segment X rounded apically, with pair of lateral papillae (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Female specimen of Mejicanotrichia harrisi Bueno-Soria &amp; Barba-Alvarez, 1999 A habitus, dorsal B head, dorsal C segments VI-X of abdomen, ventral D bursa copulatrix ventral. Scale bars: 1 mm (A); 800 µm (B); 200 µm (C); 30 µm (D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1111.77413.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/712649" pageId="0" pageNumber="355">3C</figureCitation>
). Bursa copulatrix mostly membranous, with pair of short and truncate lobes extended posteriorly; medially with keyhole-shaped opening and a shield-shaped sclerite (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Female specimen of Mejicanotrichia harrisi Bueno-Soria &amp; Barba-Alvarez, 1999 A habitus, dorsal B head, dorsal C segments VI-X of abdomen, ventral D bursa copulatrix ventral. Scale bars: 1 mm (A); 800 µm (B); 200 µm (C); 30 µm (D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1111.77413.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/712649" pageId="0" pageNumber="355">3D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="355" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="355">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="355">
The specimens exhibit a keyhole-shaped opening in the bursa copulatrix, which occurs in the other species of the genus. On the other hand, females of 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. harrisi" pageId="0" pageNumber="355" rank="species" species="harrisi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="355">M. harrisi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differ from those of other species because of the presence of two short and membranous lobes that extend posteriorly, as well as for having a shield-shaped posterior sclerite (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Female specimen of Mejicanotrichia harrisi Bueno-Soria &amp; Barba-Alvarez, 1999 A habitus, dorsal B head, dorsal C segments VI-X of abdomen, ventral D bursa copulatrix ventral. Scale bars: 1 mm (A); 800 µm (B); 200 µm (C); 30 µm (D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1111.77413.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/712649" pageId="0" pageNumber="355">3D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
